ndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFaith: Jewish Perspectives explores important questions in both modern and premodern Jewish philosophy regarding the idea of faith. Is believing a voluntary action, or do believers find themselves within the experience of faith against their will? Can faith be understood through other means (psychological, epistemic, and so forth), or is it only comprehensible from the inside, that is, from within the religious world? Is a subjective experience of faith fundamentally communicative, meaning that it includes intelligible and transmittable universal elements, or is it a private experience that we can point to or talk about through indirect means (poetic, lyrical, and so forth), but never fully decipher? This book presents various manifestations of the concept of faith in Judaism as a tradition engaged in a dialogue with the outside world. It will function as an opening and an invitation to an ongoing conversation with faith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFaith (Judaism) 0aJewish philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aBar-On, Shraga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Eliezer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershkowitz, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemberger, Dorit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolin, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, Zvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiron, Ronny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Tamar, ec